node.text:
Interviewed by our volunteer - Kavya Agarwal 
Anima
33 years old
Kalyanpur, near Diamond Line
I work as a house help during the day and return home at night where I live with my mother, father and son. However, when the lockdown was announced by the government, i was working and due to the restrictions placed on travel there was no way i could travel back home. I was stuck, miles away from my home and family, with no way of returning. On speaking to them, I was informed that my mother, who is the only other earning member in our family would not be able to go to her place of work and this would mean that our income in the months spent under lockdown would be diminished greatly, almost halved. 
Things were already bad, with my family surviving on limited remuneration and constantly on edge about catching the virus due to extremely terrible sanitation and hygiene conditions in our neighbourhood, when we were hit by Amphan. I was still staying at the house I work in, and on the evening when the storm made landfall, all lines were destroyed, cutting off power and 
network throughout the city. I was not able to contact my family at home or my married daughter and I was terrified of what conditions they must be in and the damage brought about on our dwelling. My fears were confirmed, when I somehow returned home on Saturday despite lockdown to see the ravaged houses and uprooted trees in my neighbourhood. A tree had fallen on top of my house and while the damage was not very great, i could see that my neighbour’s house was in ruins with absolutely no way of repairing it. The situation was so bad that even 3 days after the storm, water was still being pumped out of houses!
“Ami jaani na ami ki korbo, gaach ta akhoon o keyo hatiye che na aar gaadi o dhukte paache na”, despite the severity of the storm, action by officials was not taken promptly and the tree on top of my house has still not been removed, with my family residing in a relative’s house. I hope we will be able to live normally again one day. 
The pain Anima and so many of the families around us are in is overwhelming. With your support, we hope to make a difference. Help us out however you can. #amphan

স্মৃতির পাতায় সুন্দরবন ।
নামটা সত্যিই সার্থক। সুন্দর ই সেখানের নদী ,বন ,জঙ্গল ও মানুষজন । সৌভাগ্যবসত জি বাংলার সুবাদে এসব দেখার সুযোগ হয়েছিল কিছু বছর আগের এই সময়ে । ওদের আপন করে নেওয়ার ক্ষমতাও চোখে পড়ার মতন।
ঠিক চার বছরের ব্যবধান ।
.
বর্তমানে আমফান এর দাপটে বড্ড ক্ষতি হয়ে গেছে ওদের। চারিদিকে জল অথচ খাবার জল নেই ।চাষের জন্য জমিও জলে ভরা। আজ অনেকদিন হল মাথার উপর ছাদ টুকুও নেই। 
অথচ ওরাই সেইদিন ছিল কত স্বাভাবিক কত প্রাণবন্ত এবং সহজ সরল। আশা রাখি ওরা ওদের মতন করেই বিপদ কাটিয়ে উঠতে পারবে।কারণ অনেক পথ চলা বাকি সুন্দরবন এর।

This was a blackboard. A scribbled one.

We school friends went to an island in Sundarbans for distributing relief materials to the affected people over there. The camp was organised in a local High school building.... After the arrangements were done, we had a a walk around the the school and the nearby premises.

In one of the classrooms of the primary division of the school we found this blackboard.

This blackboard told us many stories of the the old days when the school used to be e filled up with students.

This blackboard took us back to those golden days of our life and made us walk down the memory lane. ➖➖➖ #blackboard #chalkart #chalk #school #village #indian #amphan #disaster #memory #memorylane #schoolfriends #friends #scribble

The physical development processes along the coast are influenced by a multitude of factors, comprising wave motions, micro and macro-tidal cycles and longshore currents typical to the coastal tract. The shore currents vary greatly along with the monsoon. These are also affected by cyclonic action, one of them being cyclone Amphan. Sundarbans has become a place of common refuge where the tribes and nature coexist, and the bounty of nature destroyed needs human help to fix the ravages of the cyclone. 
Organizations like SSGN, WPSI, and Nature Environment & Wildlife Society amongst a few are working tirelessly to ascertain the damage and help Sundarbans get back on its feet.

How can you help? Check out the link in the bio and donate whatever little you can to contribute towards the efforts towards Sundarbans.

node.text:
Super Cyclone Strom Amphan was a very powerful tropical cyclone in the Bay of Bengal. Parts of West Bengal, Orissa and Bangladesh is largely affected. Few impacts are seen in some parts of Bihar and other neighbouring states. This is the strongest cyclone ever experienced since 1999 with a wind speed of 185 mph which devastated the coastal line of the states. Amphan's forecast track placed 38.9 million people in India and Bangladesh at risk of exposure to the storm's winds, according to the US Pacific Disaster Center.

node.text:
Mentaid reached out to 45 families of children with disabilities, on 23rd and 24th May 2020, during the covid 19 lockdown with dry rations, to help sustain them. It was a big challenge as cyclone Amphan struck and the packed rations had to be distributed to the homes amidst uprooted trees, lack of electricity, water and mobile connectivity. A majority of these children receive education and training at Mentaid and were thrilled with the surprise.

node.text:
Sundarbans is in ruins after the severe impact of cyclone Amphan. The words Sundarban translate to ‘beautiful forest’ decorated with roots of mangroves that inhabit some of the most vibrant and diverse species from the Bengal Tiger to the Gangetic Dolphins, Barasinghas to the Mangrove Whistler and Alligators. With a cyclone that lasted for 5 days, from 16th to 21st May 2020, all the beautiful flora and fauna has been disturbed. The wildlife fences have been uprooted, making humans vulnerable to already agitated animals. We need to focus on helping restore the natural habitat by providing whatever means and resources we can. 
Organizations like SSGN, WPSI, and Nature Environment & Wildlife Society amongst a few are working tirelessly to ascertain the damage and help Sundarbans get back on its feet.

How can you help? Check out the link in the bio and donate whatever little you can to contribute towards the efforts towards Sundarbans.

node.text:
The last few days have taught us the value of “a roof above our head” and “food on the table”…necessities that have become never-ending nightmares for thousands as they scramble to rebuild homes and feed families after #CycloneAmphan has left nothing but destruction behind…. Day 3 yesterday was spent at Kultuli…roads are in bad condition, acres of land lay spoilt due to salinity and locals have already exhausted the little stock of food they had in storage….we distributed around 300 packets of supplies, along with tarpaulin sheets too...our day ended with a visit to Patuli where we provided some essentials. 
Yet another successful endeavor thanks to some wonderful people pitching in… while we are on the ground, the teary eyes and heartwarming smiles keep reminding us that it wouldn’t be possible to move ahead in this noble cause without your help, support, and prayers! 
Your contribution means a lot….it doesn’t always have to be monetary…you can provide dry foods, medicines, sanitary napkins, old clothes….even if you can pass on the name of a contact who has better reach, that would be useful in such situations…like I have said every bit matters... let us all do what we can! Thanks 🙏 .
.
